<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910903-0034</DOCNO><DOCID>910903-0034.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Atlantic Monthly Press   Is Sold to Insider's Group</HL><DATE>09/03/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Atlantic Monthly Press, which was to be boughtby Charles E. Tuttle Co., has instead been sold to aninsider, senior editor Morgan Entrekin and a group ofinvestors. Terms weren't disclosed.   Mr. Entrekin said that he and his backers now own about90% of the small, independent publisher, which had been ownedby businessman and writer Carl Navarre. The investors includeBrian McVeigh, a senior vice president of Nomura Securities,who is also the press's new financial adviser, the companysaid. Mr. Entrekin will become president and publisher.</LP><TEXT>   Atlantic Monthly Press, founded by the magazine of thesame name but spun off from it in 1986, has been publishingabout 50 titles a year and will have sales in 1991 of about$6 million. The well-respected press has been losing moneybut is expected to become profitable this year, said Mr.Entrekin.   There were no explanations given about why talks brokedown with Tuttle, a closely held Boston publisher thatspecializes in Asian-related subjects.</TEXT></DOC>